glish translation\n* Materials on Maori are included in the open access [[Arthur Capell]] collections ([http://catalog.paradisec.org.au/collections/AC1 AC1] and [http://catalog.paradisec.org.au/collections/AC2 AC2]) held by [[Paradisec]].\n\n{{M\u0101ori}}\n{{Languages of New Zealand}}\n{{Polynesian languages}}\n{{New Zealand topics}}\n{{Oceania topic|Languages of}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maori Language}}\n[[Category:Endangered Austronesian languages]]\n[[Category:Polynesian languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:M\u0101ori language| ]]\n[[Category:Tahitic languages]]\n", "name_user": "125.238.115.37", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C4%81ori_language"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tennessee", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Tennessee, United States}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tennessee\n| width           = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| map1            = COVID-19 Cases in Tennessee by counties.svg\n| legend1         = Map of cases by county as of April 16\n{{legend|#FFE4A3|1\u20139}}{{legend|#F2A88D|10\u201349}}{{legend|#E57814|50\u201399}}{{legend|#FF0000|100\u2013249}}{{legend|#A81C1B|> 250}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Tennessee]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[Williamson County, Tennessee|Williamson County]]\n| arrival_date    = March 5, 2020\n| date            = \n| origin          = \n| type            = \n| confirmed_cases = 6,589<ref name=\"Official Tennessee stats\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| hospitalized_cases = 711<ref name=\"Official Tennessee stats\"/>\n| recovery_cases  = 3,017<ref name=\"Official Tennessee stats\"/>\n| deaths          = 142<ref name=\"Official Tennessee stats\"/>\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://www.tn.gov/health/cedep/ncov.html}}\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Tennessee]] on March 5, 2020. As of April 17, 2020, there are 6,589 confirmed cases, 142 deaths, and 3,017 recoveries.<ref name=\"Official Tennessee stats\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tn.gov/health/cedep/ncov.html|title=Novel Coronavirus|date=April 14, 2020|website=tn.gov|language=en|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n[[File:Spread of COVID-19 Cases in Tennessee.gif|thumb|Animated map of the spread of coronavirus starting March 11]]\nOn March 5, the first case of [[COVID-19]] was reported in Tennessee, in Williamson County. The patient is a 44-year-old adult man and resident of Williamson County who recently flew on a nonstop flight to Boston through Nashville's airport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/health/2020/03/05/coronavirus-tennessee-department-health-bill-lee/4962037002/|title=Coronavirus case detected in Tennessee: First patient is quarantined in Williamson County|last=Kelman|first=Brett|last2=Ebert|first2=Joel|website=The Tennessean|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Fiona Whelan Prine, wife and manager of [[country folk]] [[singer-songwriter]] [[John Prine]] announced that she had coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2020/03/19/fiona-whelan-prine-wife-john-prine-has-coronavirus/2876152001/|title=Fiona Whelan Prine, manager and wife of John Prine, has coronavirus: 'Please stay at home'|first=Dave|last=Paulson|website=The Tennessean}}</ref> On March 26, John was admitted to the hospital after suffering sudden onset of COVID-19 symptoms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/john-prine-covid-19-symptoms-974909/|title=John Prine Hospitalized With COVID-19 Symptoms: 'His Situation Is Critical'|first1=Daniel|last1=Kreps|date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>  On April 7, John died, while Fiona had recovered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/07/arts/07reuters-people-john-prine.html|title=Country Folk Singer John Prine Dies at 73 of Coronavirus Complications|date=April 7, 2020|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, the first death was reported in Nashville.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/health/2020/03/20/first-coronavirus-death-tennessee-reported-nashville-davidson-county/2886440001/|title=Nashville health department reports Tennessee's first coronavirus death|first=Emily R.|last=West|website=The Tennessean}}</ref>\n\nThe [[University of Tennessee]] reported its first confirmed case of COVID-19 on March 22. The case involved a staff member of the university and was confirmed by the Knox County Health Department.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utk.edu/coronavirus/updates/first-confirmed-case-of-covid-19-in-our-campus-community|title=First confirmed case of COVID-19 in our campus community|website=The University of Tennessee Knoxville|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, [[Middle Tennessee State University]] confirmed an on-campus student tested positive for COVID-19 and is being supported by MTSU Student Health Services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mtsu.edu/coronavirus/archive/post/79/march-26-from-president-mcphee-covid-19-update|title=MARCH 26: From President McPhee: COVID-19 Update|website=Middle Tennessee State University|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n===Confirmed cases by date===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n! colspan=\"3\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Tennessee<ref name=\"Official Tennessee stats\"/><br />\n|-\n! Date !! Cases !! Total Deaths\n|-\n|Apr 17\n|6589\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|142\n|-\n|Apr 16\n|6262\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|141\n|-\n|Apr 15\n|6079\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|135\n|-\n|Apr 14\n|5823\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|124\n|-\n|Apr 13\n|5610\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|109\n|-\n|Apr 12\n|5308\n|101\n|-\n|Apr 11\n|5114\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|101\n|-\n|Apr 10\n|4862\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|98\n|-\n|Apr 9\n|4634\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|94\n|-\n|Apr 8\n|4362\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|79\n|-\n|Apr 7\n|4138\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|72\n|-\n|Apr 6\n|3802\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|65\n|-\n|Apr 5\n|3633\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|44\n|-\n|Apr 4\n|3321\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|43\n|-\n|Apr 3\n|3067\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|37\n|-\n|Apr 2\n|2845\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|32\n|-\n|Apr 1\n|2683\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|24\n|-\n|Mar 31\n|2239\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|21\n|-\n|Mar 30\n|1834\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|13\n|-\n|Mar 29\n|1537\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|7\n|-\n|Mar 28\n|1373\n|6\n|-\n|Mar 27\n|1203\n|style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|6\n|-\n|Mar 26\n|957\n|3\n|-\n| Mar 25 || 784 || style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|3\n|-\n| Mar 24 || 667 || 2\n|-\n| Mar 23 || 615 || 2\n|-\n| Mar 22 || 505 || style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"|2\n|-\n| Mar 21 || 371 || 1\n|-\n| Mar 20 || 228 ||style=\"background: #FFE6E6\"| 1\n|-\n| Mar 19 || 154 || 0\n|-\n| Mar 18 || 98 || 0\n|-\n| Mar 17 || 73 || 0\n|-\n| Mar 16 || 52 || 0\n|-\n| Mar 15 || 39 || 0\n|-\n| Mar 14 || 32 || 0\n|-\n| Mar 13 || 26 || 0\n|-\n| Mar 12 || 18 || 0\n|-\n| Mar 11 || 9 || 0\n|-\n| Mar 10 || 7 || 0\n|-\n| Mar 9 || 4 || 0\n|-\n| Mar 8 || 3 || 0\n|-\n| Mar 7 || 2-3 || 0\n|}\n\n==Government response==\n[[File:Springfield TN Kroger's during the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic.jpg|thumb|A half-empty shelf in the laundry detergent aisle at [[Kroger]] in [[Springfield, Tennessee|Springfield]].]]\n\nOn March 5, Governor [[Bill Lee (Tennessee politician)|Bill Lee]] reported the state's first case: a man in his 40s in [[Williamson County, Tennessee|Williamson County]] who had recently traveled outside the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newschannel5.com/news/gov-bill-lee-tennessee-health-department-to-hold-press-conference-on-coronavirus|title=Gov. Bill Lee announces first confirmed case of coronavirus in Williamson County|last=Bowles|first=Laken|date=March 5, 2020|publisher=[[WTVF]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305211436/https://www.newschannel5.com/news/gov-bill-lee-tennessee-health-department-to-hold-press-conference-on-coronavirus|archive-date=March 5, 2020|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, Governor Lee issued Executive Order No. 14 to declare a State of Emergency until it expires on May 11.  The order allows pharmacists to dispense an additional 30-day prescription provided it is to prevent the spread of the virus, allows for alternate COVID-19 testing sites provided that the Tennessee Medical Laboratory Board is notified, restricts an [[Price gouging|excessive price increase]] of items and services until March 27, suspends maximum size limitations for vehicles participating in preventing the spread of the virus, and gives the Tennessee Commissioner of Human Services the ability to waive child care requirements as needed.<ref>[https://publications.tnsosfiles.com/pub/execorders/exec-orders-lee14.pdf Executive Order \u2013 Lee No. 14] Tennessee Secretary of State</ref>\n\n[[File:Long line at grocery store in Smyrna.jpg|thumb|A long line of customers at [[Publix]] in [[Smyrna, Tennessee|Smyrna]].]]\n\nOn March 13, the [[Tennessee Supreme Court]] under Chief Justice [[Jeffrey S. Bivins|Jeff Bivins]] issued a State of Emergency order applying to the Tennessee judicial branch.  The order suspended in-person proceedings until March 31, and extended statutes of limitations and orders of protection that would expire on April 5 or before to April 6.<ref>Laken Bowles [https://www.newschannel5.com/news/tennessee-supreme-court-will-keep-courts-open-suspend-in-person-proceedings-amid-covid-19-concerns Tennessee Supreme Court will keep courts open, suspend in-person proceedings amid COVID-19 concerns] Mar 13, 2020 [[WTVF]]</ref> Additionally, Governor Lee banned traveling be state employees for non-essential government business, while also banning visitors and tours in Nashville.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kruesi |first1=Kimberlee |title=Lee closes Capitol, halts state travel over coronavirus |url=https://apnews.com/e5377df0a45885f905c52460e98fce09 |website=www.apnews.com |publisher=Associated Press |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The [[Tennessee General Assembly]] also banned the public from the [[Cordell Hull State Office Building|legislative Cordell Hull Office complex]] with only members, staff, and media allowed.<ref>[https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/13/tennessee-capitol-closes-public-over-coronavirus-legislature-not-adjourn/5047459002/ Tennessee Capitol, legislative office building close to public amid coronavirus concerns] ''The Tennessean''</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Nashville mayor [[John Cooper (Tennessee politician)|John Cooper]] announced that bars will close across the county and imposed limitations on restaurants.<ref name=\":12a\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/2020/03/15/coronavirus-tennessee-latest-news-virus-national-emergency/5052035002/|title=Coronavirus in Tennessee latest news: Restaurant restrictions, ACMs delayed and 39 confirmed cases in Tennessee|website=The Tennessean|language=en|accessdate=2020-03-16}}</ref> On the same day, Governor [[Bill Lee (Tennessee politician)|Bill Lee]] asked schools to close by March 20;<ref>{{cite news |title=Tennessee governor urges all schools to close to prevent spread of COVID-19 |url=https://www.wmcactionnews5.com/2020/03/16/tennessee-governor-urges-all-schools-close-prevent-spread-covid-/ |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=WMCActionNews5 com}}</ref> on April 15, he recommended they stay closed through the end of the school year.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tennessee schools close at governor\u2019s request while state battles coronavirus |url=https://www.wmcactionnews5.com/2020/04/15/gov-lee-closes-all-tennessee-schools-remainder-school-year/ |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=WMCActionNews5 com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Governor recommends closing Tennessee schools for the rest of the academic year |url=https://clarksvillenow.com/local/governor-recommends-closing-tennessee-schools-for-the-rest-of-the-academic-year/ |work=ClarksvilleNow.com}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Memphis mayor [[Jim Strickland (politician)|Jim Strickland]] and Shelby County mayor [[Lee Harris (politician)|Lee Harris]] issued executive orders to take effect 6:00&nbsp;PM, March 24, requiring residents to remain at home unless they serve essential services.<ref name=\"Strickland01\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.commercialappeal.com/story/news/2020/03/23/memphis-mayor-jim-strickland-issues-safer-at-home-executive-order/2898050001/|title=Memphis' 'safer at home' executive order: What is an essential service?|website=The Commercial Appeal|language=en|accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref>  The list of essential services is broad.<ref name=\"Strickland02\">{{Cite web|url=https://covid19.memphistn.gov/listing-of-essential-and-nonessential-services-3-23/|title=Listing of Essential and Nonessential Services |website=City of Memphis|language=en|accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nThe state has gradually become more transparent in its reporting. Tennessee began its battle against the COVID-19 pandemic by refusing to reveal the counties where infected victims lived. On March 10 they began revealing such information, but they still hid information regarding age and gender; now such information is published daily. On March 31 the state decided to reveal the number of negative cases in each county. Governor Lee also signed an executive order allowing local governments to meet remotely after the GOP-dominated legislature failed to do so.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kruesi |first1=Kimberlee |title=Tennessee grapples with what to disclose amid virus outbreak |url=https://apnews.com/5f9bab21e90c5a6c0c6324c5fdc2fe9b |website=apnews.com |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |date=April 1, 2020 |quote=Lee has also had to take executive action to let local counties and cities meet remotely after the GOP-dominant Legislature failed to do so in the final hours before abruptly passing an emergency spending plan for the upcoming fiscal year and recessing due to coronavirus concerns.}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, Governor Lee announced that he would sign Executive Order No. 23, which would call for all residents to stay home through April 14, unless they are carrying out essential activities.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gov. Bill Lee issues stay-at-home order through April 14 |url=https://communityimpact.com/nashville/franklin-brentwood/coronavirus/2020/03/30/gov-bill-lee-issues-statewide-stay-at-home-order-for-tennesseans/ |accessdate=April 16, 2020 |work=Community Impact Newspaper |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> On April 13, Governor Lee extended the order to the end of the month, to align with [[Donald Trump|President Trump's]] plans for businesses to reopen in early May.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tennessee Gov. Bill Lee extends stay at home order through end of April |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/politics/2020/04/13/tennessee-gov-bill-lee-extends-stay-home-order-through-end-april/2982579001/ |accessdate=April 16, 2020 |work=Tennessean |date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nOn March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis Grizzlies]].<ref name=nba>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>  In the [[National Hockey League]], the season was suspended for an indefinite amount of time, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Nashville Predators season|Nashville Predators]].<ref name=nhl>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] NHL, March 12, 2020</ref> The [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Tennessee medical cases chart}}\n{{clear}}\n\n===Confirmed cases by county===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Tennessee<ref name=\"Official Tennessee stats\"/>\nApril 14, 2020 \n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed<br>\ncases\n! scope=\"col\" |Deaths\n!'''Recov.'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Anderson County, Tennessee|Anderson]] \n| 15\n| 1\n| 10\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Bedford County, Tennessee|Bedford]]\n| 25\n| 2\n| 4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Benton County, Tennessee|Benton]]\n| 4\n| 0\n| 2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Bledsoe County, Tennessee|Bledsoe]]\n| 8\n|0\n| 3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Blount County, Tennessee|Blount]]\n| 47\n| 3\n| 36\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Bradley County, Tennessee|Bradley]]\n| 33\n|\n|24\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Campbell County, Tennessee|Campbell]]\n| 12\n|\n| 7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Cannon County, Tennessee|Cannon]]\n| 7\n| \n| 2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Carroll County, Tennessee|Carroll]]\n| 12\n|\n| 7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Carter County, Tennessee|Carter]]\n| 3\n|1\n| 2\