ision film\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Flash (Jeff Beck album)|Ambitious]]'' \n| Cameo\n| [[Jeff Beck]] music video\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Mulan (1998 film)|Mulan]]''\n| Captain Li Shang \n| Singing voice only (\"[[I'll Make a Man Out of You]]\")\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Joseph and the Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat (film)|Joseph and the Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat]]''\n| Joseph\n| Direct-to-video film produced by [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]]\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Bob the Builder|Bob the Builder: Built to be Wild]]'' \n| Jackaroo\n| Direct-to-video film\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[White & Nerdy]]'' \n| Dancer\n| [[\"Weird Al\" Yankovic]] music video parady of [[Chamillionaire]]'s \"[[Ridin']]\" feat. [[Krayzie Bone]]\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[College Road Trip]]''\n| Doug Greenhut\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Feature film\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n*[http://donny.com Donny Osmond Official website]\n*{{IMDb name|5287|Donny Osmond}}\n*{{IBDB name}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080516085632/http://www.afewmomentswith.com/ Donny Osmond Interview on Fox News Radio]\n*[http://www.osmondheaven.com Osmondheaven] Popular Fan Site\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Boomer Esiason]] and [[Meredith Vieira]]| title=Host of [[Miss America]]<br><small>with [[Marie Osmond]]</small>| years=1999\u20132000| after=[[Tony Danza]]}}\n{{succession box|before=[[John Davidson (entertainer)|John Davidson]]| title=Host of ''[[Pyramid (game show)|Pyramid]]''| years=2002\u20132004|after=[[Mike Richards (television personality)|Mike Richards]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|''Dancing with the Stars'' (US)]] winners | before=[[Shawn Johnson East|Shawn Johnson]] & [[Mark Ballas]]| years=Season 9<br>(Fall 2009 with [[Kym Herjavec|Kym Johnson]])|after= [[Nicole Scherzinger]] and [[Derek Hough]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Donny Osmond}}\n{{The Osmonds}}\n{{Dancing with the Stars (United States)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Osmond, Donny}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Orange County, California]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Utah]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American child singers]]\n[[Category:American country rock singers]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American keyboardists]]\n[[Category:American saxophonists]]\n[[Category:American male saxophonists]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American game show hosts]]\n[[Category:American Latter Day Saints]]\n[[Category:American male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:American male pop singers]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Child pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Dancing with the Stars (American TV series) winners]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from California]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from Utah]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:MGM Records artists]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:People from Ogden, Utah]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Ogden, Utah]]\n[[Category:The Osmonds members]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Osmond family (show business)]]\n[[Category:20th-century saxophonists]]\n[[Category:21st-century saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Utah]]\n[[Category:People with social anxiety disorder]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n[[Category:American male child actors]]\n[[Category:American male dancers]]\n[[Category:The Masked Singer (American TV series) contestants]]\n", "name_user": "Jmeservy", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donny_Osmond"}
{"title_page": "Berkeley Yacc", "text_new": "{{short description|Unix program for parser generation}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = Berkeley Yacc\n| logo =\n| author = Robert Corbett\n| developer = [[Thomas Dickey]]\n| released = {{Start date and age|1989|09|02}}<ref name=\"Corbett1989zoo\">{{cite newsgroup |last1=Corbett |first1=Robert |date=1989-09-02 |df=mdy |title=PD LALR(1) parser generator |newsgroup=comp.compilers |message-id=1989Sep2.134244.1611@esegue.uucp |url=https://groups.google.com/d/msg/comp.compilers/_Ad8HeBMygg/-NwkEGno1KkJ |accessdate=2017-08-26}}</ref>\n| discontinued = <!-- Set to yes if software is discontinued, otherwise omit. -->\n| ver layout = <!-- simple (default) or stacked -->\n| latest release version = 20191125\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2019|11|25}}\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| programming language = [[ANSI C]]\n| operating system = [[Unix-like]]\n| platform = \n| genre = [[Parser generator]]\n| license =  [[public domain]] \n}}\n'''Berkeley Yacc''' ('''byacc''') is a [[Unix]] [[parser generator]] designed to be compatible with [[Yacc]]. It was originally written by Robert Corbett and released in 1989.<ref>{{citation |title=lex & yacc |author1=Doug Brown |author2=John Levine |author3=Tony Mason |publisher=O'Reilly Media |edition=2 |date=October 1992}}</ref> Due to its liberal license and because it was faster than the AT&T Yacc, it quickly became the most popular version of Yacc.<ref>{{citation |title=flex & bison |author=John Levine |publisher=O'Reilly Media |date=August 2009 }}</ref> It has the advantages of being written in [[ANSI C]] and being [[public domain]] software.\n\nIt contains features not available in Yacc, such as reentrancy, which is implemented in a way that is broadly compatible with [[GNU bison|bison]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://invisible-island.net/byacc/byacc.html |title=Berkeley Yacc|quote=...support for reentrant code, which has evolved in byacc to the point where it can be compared and tuned against bison.}}</ref><ref>[http://invisible-island.net/byacc/CHANGES.html#t20100607 Berkeley Yacc Change log, see entry \"2010-06-07 Andres.Meji\"]</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1985 Robert Corbett developed an original [[LALR parser generator]] based on a paper published in the October 1982 issue of [[ACM Transactions on Programming Languages and Systems|TOPLAS]] by DeRemer and Pennello.<ref name=\"DeRemerPennello1982\">{{cite journal |last1=DeRemer |first1=Frank |last2=Pennello |first2=Thomas |date=October 1982 |title=Efficient Computation of LALR(1) Look-Ahead Sets |url=http://3e8.org/pub/scheme/doc/parsing/Efficient%20Computation%20of%20LALR%281%29%20Look-Ahead%20Sets.pdf |journal=[[ACM Transactions on Programming Languages and Systems|ACM Trans. Program. Lang. Syst.]] |volume=4 |issue=4 |pages=615\u2013649  |publisher=[[Association for Computing Machinery|ACM]] |issn=0164-0925 |doi=10.1145/69622.357187 |accessdate=2017-08-26}}</ref> Corbett wrote it as part of his research towards the Ph.D. he received from [[University of California, Berkeley]] in June 1985.<ref name=\"Corbett1988\">{{cite newsgroup |last1=Corbett |first1=Robert |date=1998-09-24 |df=mdy |title=Re: Anyone extended MAXTABLE in yacc parsers? |newsgroup=comp.compilers |message-id=98-09-125@comp.compilers |url=https://groups.google.com/d/msg/comp.compilers/iTMQr4mebqk/ll6xkOUPK-IJ |accessdate=2017-08-26}}</ref><ref name=\"Corbett1985thesis\">{{cite thesis |last1=Corbett |first1=Robert Paul |date=June 1985 |title=Static Semantics and Compiler Error Recovery |type=Ph.D. |publisher=[[University of California, Berkeley]] |id=[[Defense Technical Information Center|DTIC]] [http://www.dtic.mil/docs/citations/ADA611756 ADA611756]}}</ref> It was originally named Byson and was incompatible with [[Yacc]] but it was subsequently renamed Bison and became the basis of [[GNU bison]]. Still in 1985, Corbett derived another Yacc-compatible LALR parser generator originally named Zeus but subsequently renamed Zoo.<ref name=\"Corbett1989names\">{{cite newsgroup |last1=Corbett |first1=Robert |date=1989-09-06 |df=mdy |title=Name that PD parser generator |newsgroup=comp.compilers |message-id=1989Sep6.152554.318@esegue.segue.boston.ma.us |url=https://groups.google.com/d/msg/comp.compilers/dNGKjVETIy4/idYq6NFKy-cJ |accessdate=2017-08-26}}</ref> Corbett published the source code for Zoo in a [[Usenet newsgroup]] but it went mostly unnoticed until later in September 1989 when Corbett posted on the comp.compilers newsgroup about putting the source code on an [[FTP server]].<ref name=\"Corbett1989zoo\"/> There was discussion about renaming it and by October 1989 it had become known as Berkeley Yacc (byacc).<ref name=\"Corbett1989byacc\">{{cite newsgroup |last1=Corbett |first1=Robert |date=1989-10-03 |df=mdy |title=Berkeley Yacc (new version) |newsgroup=comp.compilers |message-id=1989Oct3.230634.1007@esegue.segue.boston.ma.us |url=https://groups.google.com/d/msg/comp.compilers/eMM4iMGBLSg/OhGrDoFhXwkJ |accessdate=2017-08-26}}</ref>\n\nA \"backtracking yacc\" (btyacc) fork of byacc was launched in 1997 by Chris Dodd. It offers [[backtracking]] and semantic disambiguation for parsing ambiguous grammar. A rule parsed but rejected by semantic information can be rolled back, so that the parser can try another rule.<ref>{{cite web |title=btyacc(1) |url=https://manpages.debian.org/stretch/btyacc/btyacc.1.en.html |website=Debian stretch \u2014 Debian Manpages}}</ref> It is the main form of byacc in [[Linux distributions]] today, as bison is typically preferred over unpatched byacc.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dodd |first1=Chris |title=ChrisDodd/btyacc |url=https://github.com/ChrisDodd/btyacc |website=GitHub |date=13 February 2019}}</ref>{{better source}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[GNU bison]] - another free software replacement for Yacc, sharing the same author as byacc.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://invisible-island.net/byacc/byacc.html Project home page for an ANSI C version]\n\n{{unix-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Parser generators]]\n[[Category:Free compilers and interpreters]]\n[[Category:Free software programmed in C]]\n[[Category:Public-domain software with source code]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Unix program for parser generation}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = Berkeley Yacc\n| logo =\n| author = Robert Corbett\n| developer = [[Thomas Dickey]]\n| released = {{Start date and age|1989|09|02}}<ref name=\"Corbett1989zoo\">{{cite newsgroup |last1=Corbett |first1=Robert |date=1989-09-02 |df=mdy |title=PD LALR(1) parser generator |newsgroup=comp.compilers |message-id=1989Sep2.134244.1611@esegue.uucp |url=https://groups.google.com/d/msg/comp.compilers/_Ad8HeBMygg/-NwkEGno1KkJ |accessdate=2017-08-26}}</ref>\n| discontinued = <!-- Set to yes if software is discontinued, otherwise omit. -->\n| ver layout = <!-- simple (default) or stacked -->\n| latest release version = 20191125\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2019|11|25}}\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| programming language = [[ANSI C]]\n| operating system = [[Unix-like]]\n| platform = \n| genre = [[Parser generator]]\n| license =  [[public domain]] \n}}\n'''Berkeley Yacc''' ('''byacc''') is a [[Unix]] [[parser generator]] designed to be compatible with [[Yacc]]. It was originally written by Robert Corbett and released in 1989.<ref>{{citation |title=lex & yacc |author1=Doug Brown |author2=John Levine |author3=Tony Mason |publisher=O'Reilly Media |edition=2 |date=October 1992}}</ref> Due to its liberal license and because it was faster than the AT&T Yacc, it quickly became the most popular version of Yacc.<ref>{{citation |title=flex & bison |author=John Levine |publisher=O'Reilly Media |date=August 2009 }}</ref> It has the advantages of being written in [[ANSI C]] and being [[public domain]] software.\n\nIt contains features not available in Yacc, such as reentrancy, which is implemented in a way that is broadly compatible with [[GNU bison|bison]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://invisible-island.net/byacc/byacc.html |title=Berkeley Yacc|quote=...support for reentrant code, which has evolved in byacc to the point where it can be compared and tuned against bison.}}</ref><ref>[http://invisible-island.net/byacc/CHANGES.html#t20100607 Berkeley Yacc Change log, see entry \"2010-06-07 Andres.Meji\"]</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1985 Robert Corbett developed an original [[LALR parser generator]] based on a paper published in the October 1982 issue of [[ACM Transactions on Programming Languages and Systems|TOPLAS]] by DeRemer and Pennello.<ref name=\"DeRemerPennello1982\">{{cite journal |last1=DeRemer |first1=Frank |last2=Pennello |first2=Thomas |date=October 1982 |title=Efficient Computation of LALR(1) Look-Ahead Sets |url=http://3e8.org/pub/scheme/doc/parsing/Efficient%20Computation%20of%20LALR%281%29%20Look-Ahead%20Sets.pdf |journal=[[ACM Transactions on Programming Languages and Systems|ACM Trans. Program. Lang. Syst.]] |volume=4 |issue=4 |pages=615\u2013649  |publisher=[[Association for Computing Machinery|ACM]] |issn=0164-0925 |doi=10.1145/69622.357187 |accessdate=2017-08-26}}</ref> Corbett wrote it as part of his research towards the Ph.D. he received from [[University of California, Berkeley]] in June 1985.<ref name=\"Corbett1988\">{{cite newsgroup |last1=Corbett |first1=Robert |date=1998-09-24 |df=mdy |title=Re: Anyone extended MAXTABLE in yacc parsers? |newsgroup=comp.compilers |message-id=98-09-125@comp.compilers |url=https://groups.google.com/d/msg/comp.compilers/iTMQr4mebqk/ll6xkOUPK-IJ |accessdate=2017-08-26}}</ref><ref name=\"Corbett1985thesis\">{{cite thesis |last1=Corbett |first1=Robert Paul |date=June 1985 |title=Static Semantics and Compiler Error Recovery |type=Ph.D. |publisher=[[University of California, Berkeley]] |id=[[Defense Technical Information Center|DTIC]] [http://www.dtic.mil/docs/citations/ADA611756 ADA611756]}}</ref> It was originally named Byson and was incompatible with [[Yacc]] but it was subsequently renamed Bison and became the basis of [[GNU bison]]. Still in 1985, Corbett derived another Yacc-compatible LALR parser generator originally named Zeus but subsequently renamed Zoo.<ref name=\"Corbett1989names\">{{cite newsgroup |last1=Corbett |first1=Robert |date=1989-09-06 |df=mdy |title=Name that PD parser generator |newsgroup=comp.compilers |message-id=1989Sep6.152554.318@esegue.segue.boston.ma.us |url=https://groups.google.com/d/msg/comp.compilers/dNGKjVETIy4/idYq6NFKy-cJ |accessdate=2017-08-26}}</ref> Corbett published the source code for Zoo in a [[Usenet newsgroup]] but it went mostly unnoticed until later in September 1989 when Corbett posted on the comp.compilers newsgroup about putting the source code on an [[FTP server]].<ref name=\"Corbett1989zoo\"/> There was discussion about renaming it and by October 1989 it had become known as Berkeley Yacc (byacc).<ref name=\"Corbett1989byacc\">{{cite newsgroup |last1=Corbett |first1=Robert |date=1989-10-03 |df=mdy |title=Berkeley Yacc (new version) |newsgroup=comp.compilers |message-id=1989Oct3.230634.1007@esegue.segue.boston.ma.us |url=https://groups.google.com/d/msg/comp.compilers/eMM4iMGBLSg/OhGrDoFhXwkJ |accessdate=2017-08-26}}</ref>\n\nA \"backtracking yacc\" (btyacc) fork of byacc was launched in 1997 by Chris Dodd. It offers [[backtracking]] and semantic disambiguation for parsing ambiguous grammar. A rule parsed but rejected by semantic information can be rolled back, so that the parser can try another rule. It is the main form of byacc in [[Linux distributions]] today, as bison is typically preferred over unpatched byacc.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dodd |first1=Chris |title=ChrisDodd/btyacc |url=https://github.com/ChrisDodd/btyacc |website=GitHub |date=13 February 2019}}</ref>{{better source}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[GNU bison]] - another free software replacement for Yacc, sharing the same author as byacc.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://invisible-island.net/byacc/byacc.html Project home page for an ANSI C version]\n\n{{unix-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Parser generators]]\n[[Category:Free compilers and interpreters]]\n[[Category:Free software programmed in C]]\n[[Category:Public-domain software with source code]]\n", "name_user": "Artoria2e5", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Berkeley_Yacc"}
{"title_page": "Life Itself (2014 film)", "text_new": "{{About|the 2014 documentary|a disambiguation page|Life Itself (disambiguation){{!}}Life Itself}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Life Itself\n| image          = Life Itself doc poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Steve James (producer)|Steve James]]\n| producer       = Zak Piper<br />Steve James<br />[[Garrett Basch]]\n| based on       = {{based on|''Life Itself: A Memoir''|[[Roger Ebert]]}}\n| starring       = [[Roger Ebert]]<br />[[Chaz Ebert]]\n| music          = Joshua Abrams\n| cinematography = Dana Kupper\n| editing        = Steve James<br />David E. Simpson\n| studio         = [[Kartemquin Films]]<br />Film Rites<br />[[CNN Films]]\n| distributor    = [[Magnolia Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2014|1|19|[[2014 Sundance Film Festival|Sundance]]|2014|07|04|United States}}\n| runtime        = 121 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 120:41--><ref>{{cite web | url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/life-itself-film | title=''LIFE ITSELF'' (15) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=October 22, 2014 | accessdate=November 17, 2014}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $810,454<ref name=\"bomojo\">{{cite web |title=Life Itself (2014) |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=lifeitself.htm |accessdate=September 15, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Life Itself''''' is a 2014 American [[Biographical film|biographical]] [[documentary film]] about [[Chicago]] film critic [[Roger Ebert]], directed by [[Steve James (producer)|Steve James]] and produced by Zak Piper, James and [[Garrett Basch]]. The film is based on Ebert's 2011 memoir of the same name.<ref name=\"Hollywood\">{{cite web |last=Kit|first=Borys|title=Roger Ebert Documentary Filmmakers Vow to Finish Movie | url= https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/roger-ebert-dead-documentary-filmmakers-433065 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=April 26, 2013 |date=April 4, 2013}}</ref> It premiered at the 2014 [[Sundance Film Festival]] and was an official selection at the 67th [[Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>Pavard, Charlotte (May 20, 2014). [http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/theDailyArticle/60980.html \"CANNES CLASSICS - Life Itself: a critic's life and times\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812211547/http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/theDailyArticle/60980.html |date=August 12, 2014 }}. [[Festival De Cannes]].</ref> The 41st [[Telluride Film Festival]] hosted a special screening of the film on August 28, 2014.<ref>Feinberg, Scott (August 31, 2014).[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/telluride-a-film-fest-knows-729301 \"Telluride: A Film Fest That Knows How to Party\"]. ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''.</ref> [[Magnolia Pictures]] released the film theatrically in the United States and simultaneously via [[video on demand]] platforms on July 4, 2014.<ref>[http://lifeitself.vhx.tv/ \"Life Itself.\"]. VHX. Retrieved December 11, 2014.</ref><ref>Tallerico, Brian. [https://www.rogerebert.com/life-itself/where-you-can-see-life-itself \"Where You Can See 'Life Itself.'\"]. rogerebert.com. 30 June 2014. 20 July 2014.</ref>\n\nOn December 2, 2014, the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] announced that the film was 1 of 15 films shortlisted in the [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature|Documentary Feature]] category for the [[87th Academy Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/oscar-documentary-feature-shortlist-announced-full-list-1201306252/||title=Oscars: Documentary Feature Shortlist At 15|publisher=Deadline|date=December 2, 2014}}</ref> but it was not nominated.  It was also nominated for two [[News & Documentary Emmy Awards]], winning the award for Outstanding Editing: Documentary & Long-Form.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emmyonline.com/news_37th_winners||title=NATIONAL ACADEMY OF TELEVISION ARTS AND SCIENCES ANNOUNCES WINNERS AT THE 37TH ANNUAL NEWS & DOCUMENTARY EMMY\u00ae AWARDS|date=September 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nThe film makes use of footage and interviews with American film critic Roger Ebert during the final months of his life interspersed with interviews of his friends, colleagues, and family including: [[Chaz Ebert]] (his wife), [[Martin Scorsese]], [[Werner Herzog]], [[Errol Morris]], and [[Ava DuVernay]], among others. The film features clips from Ebert's popular television show with [[Gene Siskel]], including outtakes, and their many appearances on shows like ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson]]'' and ''[[Late Night with David Letterman]]''. The film also explores the relationship between Siskel and Ebert, Roger's friendship with [[Russ Meyer]] and their collaboration on ''[[Beyond the Valley of the Dolls]]'', as well as how Roger ultimately came to transcend film criticism to become an influential cultural voice.\n\n==Production==\nOn September 7, 2012, a [[film adaptation]] of the 2011 memoir ''Life Itself'' was first announced by Ebert on [[Twitter]]: \"Whoa! My memoir has been optioned for a doc by Steve James (''[[Hoop Dreams]]''), with [[Martin Scorsese]] and [[Steven Zaillian]] as exec producers.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Ebert|first=Roger|title=Twitter / ebertchicago: Whoa! My memoir has been optioned ...|url=https://twitter.com/ebertchicago/status/244082119679303680|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=26 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nSteve James said:  \"That\u2019s what made me want to do the movie: the way in which his life had this extraordinary desire for adventure and then, of course, he did his share of suffering and soldiering on. And all of that informed the kind of critic he became. It informed his reviews. It informed everything about who he was and what we came to collectively love about him.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/life-itself-director-steve-james-explains-why-roger-ebert-deserved-a-documentary-20140705|title=\u2018Life Itself\u2019 Director Steve James Explains Why Roger Ebert Deserved a Documentary|first=Eric|last=Kohn|date=July 5, 2014|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn April 4, 2013, following Ebert's death, the filmmakers expressed their condolences and promised to finish the film.<ref>{{cite web|title=Twitter / EbertDoc: We are devastated. But we will continue. We will ...|url=https://twitter.com/EbertDoc/statuses/319901622669029376|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=April 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lussier|first=German|title=Steve James Vows To Finish \u2018Life Itself,\u2019 The Roger Ebert Documentary|url= https://www.slashfilm.com/steve-james-vows-to-finish-life-itself-the-roger-ebert-documentary/|publisher=SlashFilm.com|accessdate=April 26, 2013|date=April 6, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lealos|first=Shawn S.|title=Roger Ebert Documentary \u2018Life Itself\u2019 Will be Finished|url=http://renegadecinema.com/4102/roger-ebert-documentary-life-itself|publisher=Renegade Cinama|accessdate=April 27, 2013|date=April 6, 2013}}</ref> On November 20, 2013, an [[Indiegogo]] campaign was launched to raise money for the film. Over $150,000 was raised.<ref>[https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/life-itself-a-feature-documentary-based-on-roger-ebert-s-memoir \"Life Itself - A feature documentary based on Roger Ebert's memoir\"]. [[Indiegogo]]. Retrieved December 11, 2014.</ref>\n\nLocations seen in the film include the [[Alfred Caldwell Lily Pool]], the [[Old Town Ale House]], the [[Chateau Marmont]], and [[Hotel Splendid]].\n\n==Release==\nOn January 18, 2013, [[CNN Films]] announced that it had acquired the rights to air ''Life Itself'' on television.<ref>{{cite web|title=CNN to air Life Itself, our Roger Ebert Doc, in 2014|url=http://kartemquin.com/news/5035/cnn-to-air-life-itself-our-roger-ebert-doc-in-2014|publisher=Kartemquin Films|accessdate=April 26, 2013|date=January 18, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Patten|first=Dominic|title=Sundance: CNN Films Makes Buying Debut; Announces Trio Of Documentaries|url= https://www.deadline.com/2013/01/sundance-film-festival-cnn-films-martin-scorsese-roger-ebert-documentaries/|publisher=Deadline.com|accessdate=26 April 2013|date=January 18, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Fernandez|first=Jay A.|title=CNN Films Acquires Roger Ebert Documentary Exec Produced by Martin Scorsese|url= https://www.indiewire.com/article/cnn-films-acquires-roger-ebert-documentary-exec-produced-by-martin-scorsese|work=Indie Wire|accessdate=April 26, 2013|date=January 19, 2013}}</ref> It premiered at the [[2014 Sundance Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kartemquin.com/news/life-itself-to-world-premiere-at-sundance-film-festival-2014|title = Life Itself to World Premiere at Sundance Film Festival 2014|date = December 9, 2013|accessdate = July 7, 2018|website = [[Kartemquin Films]]}}</ref> [[Magnolia Pictures]] released the film theatrically in the US on July 4, 2014.<ref name=\"mag\"/> [[Dogwoof]] released the film in the UK on November 14, 2014.<ref>[https://www.rogerebert.com/life-itself/strolling-through-roger-eberts-perfect-london-walk \"Strolling Through Roger Ebert's 'Perfect London Walk'\"]. rogerebert. November 14, 2014.</ref> The film aired on [[CNN]] January 4, 2015.<ref name=\"mag\">{{cite web|url=http://kartemquin.com/news/magnolia-pictures-to-distribute-life-itself|title=Magnolia Pictures to distribute Life Itself|publisher=[[Kartemquin Films]]|date=4 February 2014|accessdate=February 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n<!--NOTE: Please remember to update accessdates when updating ratings. Thank you.-->\n''Life Itself'' has received universal acclaim from critics.<ref>[https://www.commonsensemedia.org/movie-reviews/life-itself-2014 Common Sense Media]</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.moviemail.com/film/dvd/Life-Itself/ | title=Life Itself | work=MovieMail | publisher=MovieMail | accessdate=January 30, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213182944/http://www.moviemail.com/film/dvd/Life-Itself/ | archive-date=February 13, 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref> On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds a rating of 97% from 198 critics, with an average rating of 8.38/10; the general consensus states: \"Rich in detail and warmly affectionate, ''Life Itself'' offers a joyful yet poignant tribute to a critical cinematic legacy.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/life_itself/ | title=Life Itself | work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher=[[Flixster]] | accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the documentary has a score of 87 out of 100, based on 35 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/life-itself | title=Life Itself Reviews | work=[[Metacritic]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate=January 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{Cite book | last=Ebert | first=Roger | coauthors= | title=Life Itself: A Memoir | ISBN=0-4465-8497-5 | year=2011 | publisher=[[Hachette Book Group USA#Current imprints|Grand Central Publishing]] | location=New York City, NY | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/lifeitselfmemoir00eber }}\n\n==See also==\n*''[[What She Said: The Art of Pauline Kael]]'', the 2018 documentary film also about a legendary film critic\n*''[[Hoop Dreams]]'', the 1994 documentary film Ebert championed\n*[[Film criticism]]\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://lifeitself.vhx.tv/}}\n* {{IMDb title|2382298|Life Itself}}\n* {{mojo title|lifeitself|Life Itself}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|life_itself|Life Itself}}\n* {{metacritic film|life-itself|Life Itself}}\n\n{{SiskelandEbert}}\n{{Steve James}}\n{{CNN Films}}\n{{Kartemquin Films}}\n{{Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Documentary Feature}}\n{{Producers Guild of America Award for Best Documentary Motion Picture}}\n{{Portal bar|Film|Biography|United States}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Life Itself}}\n[[Category:2014 films]]\n[[Category:2010s documentary films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:American biographical films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Steve James]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about journalists]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about writers]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about writers]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about journalists]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about Chicago]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about the film industry]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about cancer]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about death]]\n[[Category:Films based on biographies]]\n[[Category:Kartemquin Films films]]\n[[Category:CNN Films films]]\n[[Category:Roger Ebert]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the 2014 documentary|a disambiguation page|Life Itself (disambiguation){{!}}Life Itself}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Life Itself\n| image          = Life Itself doc poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Steve James (producer)|Steve James]]\n| producer       = Zak Piper<br />Steve James<br />[[Garrett Basch]]\n| based on       = {{based on|''Life Itself: A Memoir''|[[Roger Ebert]]}}\n| starring       = [[Roger Ebert]]<br />[[Chaz Ebert]]\n| music          = Joshua Abrams\n| cinematography = Dana Kupper\n| editing        = Steve James<br />David E. Simpson\n| studio         = [[Kartemquin Films]]<br />Film Rites<br />[[CNN Films]]\n| distributor    = [[Magnolia Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2014|1|19|[[2014 Sundance Film Festival|Sundance]]|2014|07|04|United States}}\n| runtime        = 121 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 120:41--><ref>{{cite web | url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/life-itself-film | title=''LIFE ITSELF'' (15) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=October 22, 2014 | accessdate=November 17, 2014}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $810,454<ref name=\"bomojo\">{{cite web |title=Life Itself (2014) |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=lifeitself.htm |accessdate=September 15, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Life Itself''''' is a 2014 American [[Biographical film|biographical]] [[documentary film]] about [[Chicago]] film critic [[Roger Ebert]], directed by [[Steve James (producer)|Steve James]] and produced by Zak Piper, James and [[Garrett Basch]]. The film is based on Ebert's 2011 memoir of the same name.<ref name=\"Hollywood\">{{cite web |last=Kit|first=Borys|title=Roger Ebert Documentary Filmmakers Vow to Finish Movie | url= https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/roger-ebert-dead-documentary-filmmakers-433065 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=April 26, 2013 |date=April 4, 2013}}</ref> It premiered at the 2014 [[Sundance Film Festival]] and was an official selection at the 67th [[Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>Pavard, Charlotte (May 20, 2014). [http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/theDailyArticle/60980.html \"CANNES CLASSICS - Life Itself: a critic's life and times\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812211547/http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/theDailyArticle/60980.html |date=August 12, 2014 }}. [[Festival De Cannes]].</ref> The 41st [[Telluride Film Festival]] hosted a special screening of the film on August 28, 2014.<ref>Feinberg, Scott (August 31, 2014).[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/telluride-a-film-fest-knows-729301 \"Telluride: A Film Fest That Knows How to Party\"]. ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''.</ref> [[Magnolia Pictures]] released the film theatrically in the United States and simultaneously via [[video on demand]] platforms on July 4, 2014.<ref>[http://lifeitself.vhx.tv/ \"Life Itself.\"]. VHX. Retrieved December 11, 2014.</ref><ref>Tallerico, Brian. [https://www.rogerebert.com/life-itself/where-you-can-see-life-itself \"Where You Can See 'Life Itself.'\"]. rogerebert.com. 30 June 2014. 20 July 2014.</ref>\n\nOn December 2, 2014, the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] announced that the film was 1 of 15 films shortlisted in the [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature|Documentary Feature]] category for the [[87th Academy Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/oscar-documentary-feature-shortlist-announced-full-list-1201306252/||title=Oscars: Documentary Feature Shortlist At 15|publisher=Deadline|date=December 2, 2014}}</ref> but it was not nominated.  It was also nominated for two [[News & Documentary Emmy Awards]], winning the award for Outstanding Editing: Documentary & Long-Form.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emmyonline.com/news_37th_winners||title=NATIONAL ACADEMY OF TELEVISION ARTS AND SCIENCES ANNOUNCES WINNERS AT THE 37TH ANNUAL NEWS & DOCUMENTARY EMMY\u00ae AWARDS|date=September 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nThe film makes use of footage and interviews with American film critic Roger Ebert during the final months of his life interspersed with interviews of his friends, colleagues, and family including: [[Chaz Ebert]] (his wife), [[Martin Scorsese]], [[Werner Herzog]], [[Errol Morris]], and [[Ava DuVernay]], among others. The film features clips from Ebert's popular television show with [[Gene Siskel]], including outtakes, and their many appearances on shows like ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson]]'' and ''[[Late Night with David Letterman]]''. The film also explores the relationship between Siskel and Ebert, Roger's friendship with [[Russ Meyer]] and their collaboration on ''[[Beyond the Valley of the Dolls]]'', as well as how Roger ultimately came to transcend film criticism to become an influential cultural voice.\n\n==Production==\nOn September 7, 2012, a [[film adaptation]] of the 2011 memoir ''Life Itself'' was first announced by Ebert on [[Twitter]]: \"Whoa! My memoir has been optioned for a doc by Steve James (''[[Hoop Dreams]]''), with [[Martin Scorsese]] and [[Steven Zaillian]] as exec producers.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Ebert|first=Roger|title=Twitter / ebertchicago: Whoa! My memoir has been optioned ...|url=https://twitter.com/ebertchicago/status/244082119679303680|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=26 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nSteve James said:  \"That\u2019s what made me want to do the movie: the way in which his life had this extraordinary desire for adventure and then, of course, he did his share of suffering and soldiering on. And all of that informed the kind of critic he became. It informed his reviews. It informed everything about who he was and what we came to collectively love about him.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/life-itself-director-steve-james-explains-why-roger-ebert-deserved-a-documentary-20140705|title=\u2018Life Itself\u2019 Director Steve James Explains Why Roger Ebert Deserved a Documentary|first=Eric|last=Kohn|date=July 5, 2014|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn April 4, 2013, following Ebert's death, the filmmakers expressed their condolences and promised to finish the film.<ref>{{cite web|title=Twitter / EbertDoc: We are devastated. But we will continue. We will ...|url=https://twitter.com/EbertDoc/statuses/319901622669029376|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=April 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lussier|first=German|title=Steve James Vows To Finish \u2018Life Itself,\u2019 The Roger Ebert Documentary|url= https://www.slashfilm.com/steve-james-vows-to-finish-life-itself-the-roger-ebert-documentary/|publisher=SlashFilm.com|accessdate=April 26, 2013|date=April 6, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lealos|first=Shawn S.|title=Roger Ebert Documentary \u2018Life Itself\u2019 Will be Finished|url=http://renegadecinema.com/4102/roger-ebert-documentary-life-itself|publisher=Renegade Cinama|accessdate=April 27, 2013|date=April 6, 2013}}</ref> On November 20, 2013, an [[Indiegogo]] campaign was launched to raise money for the film. Over $150,000 was raised.<ref>[https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/life-itself-a-feature-documentary-based-on-roger-ebert-s-memoir \"Life Itself - A feature documentary based on Roger Ebert's memoir\"]. [[Indiegogo]]. Retrieved December 11, 2014.</ref>\n\nLocations seen in the film include the [[Alfred Caldwell Lily Pool]], the [[Old Town Ale House]], the [[Chateau Marmont]], and [[Hotel Splendid]].\n\n==Release==\nOn January 18, 2013, [[CNN Films]] announced that it had acquired the rights to air ''Life Itself'' on television.<ref>{{cite web|title=CNN to air Life Itself, our Roger Ebert Doc, in 2014|url=http://kartemquin.com/news/5035/cnn-to-air-life-itself-our-roger-ebert-doc-in-2014|publisher=Kartemquin Films|accessdate=April 26, 2013|date=January 18, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Patten|first=Dominic|title=Sundance: CNN Films Makes Buying Debut; Announces Trio Of Documentaries|url= https://www.deadline.com/2013/01/sundance-film-festival-cnn-films-martin-scorsese-roger-ebert-documentaries/|publisher=Deadline.com|accessdate=26 April 2013|date=January 18, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Fernandez|first=Jay A.|title=CNN Films Acquires Roger Ebert Documentary Exec Produced by Martin Scorsese|url= https://www.indiewire.com/article/cnn-films-acquires-roger-ebert-documentary-exec-produced-by-martin-scorsese|work=Indie Wire|accessdate=April 26, 2013|date=January 19, 2013}}</ref> It premiered at the [[2014 Sundance Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kartemquin.com/news/life-itself-to-world-premiere-at-sundance-film-festival-2014|title = Life Itself to World Premiere at Sundance Film Festival 2014|date = December 9, 2013|accessdate = July 7, 2018|website = [[Kartemquin Films]]}}</ref> [[Magnolia Pictures]] released the film theatrically in the US on July 4, 2014.<ref name=\"mag\"/> [[Dogwoof]] released the film in the UK on November 14, 2014.<ref>[https://www.rogerebert.com/life-itself/strolling-through-roger-eberts-perfect-london-walk \"Strolling Through Roger Ebert's 'Perfect London Walk'\"]. rogerebert. November 14, 2014.</ref> The film aired on [[CNN]] January 4, 2015.<ref name=\"mag\">{{cite web|url=http://kartemquin.com/news/magnolia-pictures-to-distribute-life-itself|title=Magnolia Pictures to distribute Life Itself|publisher=[[Kartemquin Films]]|date=4 February 2014|accessdate=February 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n<!--NOTE: Please remember to update accessdates when updating ratings. Thank you.-->\n''Life Itself'' has received universal acclaim from critics.<ref>[https://www.commonsensemedia.org/movie-reviews/life-itself-2014 Common Sense Media]</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.moviemail.com/film/dvd/Life-Itself/ | title=Life Itself | work=MovieMail | publisher=MovieMail | accessdate=January 30, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213182944/http://www.moviemail.com/film/dvd/Life-Itself/ | archive-date=February 13, 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref> On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds a rating of 97% from 185 critics, with an average rating of 8.4/10; the general consensus states: \"Rich in detail and warmly affectionate, ''Life Itself'' offers a joyful yet poignant tribute to a critical cinematic legacy.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/life_itself/ | title=Life Itself | work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher=[[Flixster]] | accessdate=January 30, 2015}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the documentary has a score of 87 out of 100, based on 35 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/life-itself | title=Life Itself Reviews | work=[[Metacritic]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate=January 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{Cite book | last=Ebert | first=Roger | coauthors= | title=Life Itself: A Memoir | ISBN=0-4465-8497-5 | year=2011 | publisher=[[Hachette Book Group USA#Current imprints|Grand Central Publishing]] | location=New York City, NY | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/lifeitselfmemoir00eber }}\n\n==See also==\n*''[[What She Said: The Art of Pauline Kael]]'', the 2018 documentary film also about a legendary film critic\n*''[[Hoop Dreams]]'', the 1994 documentary film Ebert championed\n*[[Film criticism]]\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://lifeitself.vhx.tv/}}\n* {{IMDb title|2382298|Life Itself}}\n* {{mojo title|lifeitself|Life Itself}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|life_itself|Life Itself}}\n* {{metacritic film|life-itself|Life Itself}}\n\n{{SiskelandEbert}}\n{{Steve James}}\n{{CNN Films}}\n{{Kartemquin Films}}\n{{Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Documentary Feature}}\n{{Producers Guild of America Award for Best Documentary Motion Picture}}\n{{Portal bar|Film|Biography|United States}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Life Itself}}\n[[Category:2014 films]]\n[[Category:2010s documentary films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:American biographical films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Steve James]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about journalists]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about writers]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about writers]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about journalists]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about Chicago]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about the film industry]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about cancer]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about death]]\n[[Category:Films based on biographies]]\n[[Category:Kartemquin Films films]]\n[[Category:CNN Films films]]\n[[Category:Roger Ebert]]\n", "name_user": "EclecticEnnui", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReception", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Life_Itself_(2014_film)"}
{"title_page": "\u00c1rp\u00e1d Bogsch", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = \u00c1rp\u00e1d Bogsch\n| image         = Arpad_Bogsch.jpg \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    =  {{Birth date|1919|02|24}}\n| birth_place   =  [[Budapest]], [[Hungarian Democratic Republic|Hungary]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2004|09|19|1919|02|24}}\n| death_place   =  [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]]\n| nationality   = [[Hungary|Hungarian]], [[United States|American]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Attorney\n| years_active  = 1942-1997\n| known_for     = Director General of [[WIPO]]\n| notable_works = Universal Copyright Convention: An Analysis and Commentary (book)\n}}\n'''\u00c1rp\u00e1d Bogsch''' (February 24, 1919, [[Budapest]], [[Hungarian Democratic Republic|Hungary]] \u2013 September 19, 2004, [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]]<ref name=\"WIPOpr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wipo.int/edocs/prdocs/en/2004/wipo_pr_2004_389.html|title=WIPO Director General Expresses Concolences on Passing of Dr. \u00c1rp\u00e1d Bogsch, Press Release 389, Geneva|date=September 21, 2004|publisher=World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO)|accessdate=30 April 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080224052745/http://www.wipo.int:80/edocs/prdocs/en/2004/wipo_pr_2004_389.html|archivedate=24 February 2008}}</ref>) was a [[Hungarian-American]] international [[civil servant]]. He became an American citizen in 1959.<ref name=\"WIPOpr\"/> From 1973 to 1997, he was Director General of [[World Intellectual Property Organization]] (WIPO). He was also Secretary General of the [[International Union for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants]] (UPOV).\n\n[[File:WIPO1.JPG|left|thumb|the \u00c1rp\u00e1d Bogsch building]] \nBogsch was featured in the 1988 Swiss documentary film ''A Szellem Tulajdona'' (''Property of the Intellect''), directed by [[Zolt\u00e1n Bonta]].<ref>{{IMDb title | id= 0378830 | title= A Szellem Tulajdona }}</ref>\n\nThere have been a number of tributes made in Bogsch's memory. The main building at WIPO headquarters in [[Geneva]] is named the \"\u00c1rp\u00e1d Bogsch building\" in his honor.<ref>{{cite web |title=Agreement with General Contractor Paves Way for Beginning of Conference Hall Construction |url=http://www.wipo.int/pressroom/en/articles/2011/article_0016.html |website=WIPO |accessdate=September 9, 2017 |language=en |date=May 31, 2011}}</ref> The Hungarian Intellectual Property Office, in the country of Bogsch's birth, features a [[Bust (sculpture)|bust]] of Bogsch by sculptor {{ill|Tibor Borb\u00e1s|hu|Borb\u00e1s Tibor}}.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u00c1rp\u00e1d Bogsch (1919 - 2004 )|url=http://www.hipo.gov.hu/en/news/sztnh-hirek/hirek-esemenyek/arpad-bogsch-1919-2004 |accessdate=September 9, 2017 |agency=Hungarian Intellectual Property Office |date=July 15, 2012 |language=en}}</ref> The [[International Federation of Inventors' Associations]] in 2010 established the \u00c1rp\u00e1d Bogsch Memory Medal, to be awarded to individuals who support invention and innovation in the same spirit as Bogsch.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u00c1rp\u00e1d Bogsch Memory Medal: The highest international recognition of invention and innovation supporters |url=http://www.invention-ifia.ch/Bogsch/Bogsch%20medal.htm |website=International Federation of Inventors' Associations |accessdate=September 9, 2017 |date=November 24,  2013}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notable works==\n* {{cite book |last1=Bogsch |first1=Arpad |title=Universal Copyright Convention: An Analysis and Commentary |date=1958 |publisher=Bowker |location=New York |lccn=58-13137 |oclc=902072883}} A comprehensive annotation of the [[Universal Copyright Convention]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{start box}}\n{{succession box|title=Director General of [[World Intellectual Property Organization]] (WIPO)|before=[[Georg Bodenhausen]]|after=[[Kamil Idris]]|years=1973&ndash;1997}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{WIPODirectorGeneral|state=uncollapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}